            },
            "answer_text": "For irrational numbers, here's an easy way to generate an irrational number which doesn't contain a specific number. Lets first choose \"9\" as the digit we don't want. Pick any irrational number. Say the root 2. Write it out in base 9. Now consider the resulting number as a base 10 decimal. It will be irrational and not contain a \"9\". Proof: The number in base 9 cannot contain a repeating pattern, or it would be rational. So considered as a base 10 number, it cannot be rational either. Generalised for any number: If you want an irrational number not containing \"4\", write it out in base 9, then swap every occurrence of \"4\" with \"9\". By the same argument, this number considered as base 10 must also be irrational. Don't think this can be generalised for transcendentals though ... ",
